Initial Insights on Integer columns:¶
  1. Balance column has negative values. It is valid.
  2. Up to 75% of the customers have not been contacted or contact period is greater than 90 days based on pdays value of -1. This looks like a potentially droppable column.
  3. Similarly, number of times the customer had been contacted is 0 upto the third quartile based on previous column. We can look at this feature in detail to determine if this can be dropped as well.
  4. Majority of the features are of 'Object' data type and has to be converted as relevant.

Insights from Univariate analysis of continuos values features:¶
  1. Age is almost normally distributed with majority of customers contacted within the age range 30-40. Boxplot shows that 70-90s are outliers.
  2. Balance is highly skewed. This may imply that having negative to low/zero balance might impact term deposits sale. So we will include that feature.
  3. Last contact day of the month seems to be almost a normal distribution across the data points. This shows that there is no significant impact from this feature on the data points. This can potentially be dropped.
  4. Last contact duration is also highly right skewed. Let's do bivariate analysis to see if spending more time talking to the customer correlates to term deposit sale.Also the larger durations are all outliers.
  5. Campaign feature is skewed but it might be beneficial to include how many times the customer was contacted for this campaign. This also has large amount of outliers.
  6. Based on Statistical summary and the dist plots, both pdays and previous columns correspond to almost 75% of the customers have either not been contacted before or contacted 900 days ago. This shows that both these features are not impacting the target variable and can be dropped.

Insights from Univariate analyses of Categorical features:¶
  1. Main observation to note is that 88% of the customers did NOT take Term Deposits.
  2. While customers with Management type jobs, technicians and blue-collar workers have been targeted mainly, the bank has also tried making term deposit sales to people who are unemployed, students who are most-likely to not have resources to make term deposits
  3. 4% of customers have education type as 'Unknown' while majority of the customer base have Secondary education level. We will treat the 'Unknown' level as part of our data preparation.
  4. 98% of the observed customers did not default and hence is a good basis to encourage them to make term deposits. Normally I would have dropped this column but given the low number of customers who ended up taking Term Deposits, we will retain this feature to make our prediction
  5. 83% of customers don't have personal loans while 16% do. Customers with personal loans may focus on repayment rather than making term deposits.
  6. % of customers Availing or not availing Housing loan is almost comparable.
  7. With 64% of customers contacted via cell and around 28% with Unknown contact type, it will be beneficial to drop this column since based on available data, it points to most customers spoken to via cell or telephone and this won't impact the sale.
  8. Months of May, June, July and August are when most of the customers have been contacted. Given that, by common logic, a customer's term deposits will run over a period of time, when they were contacted would not make an impact.
  9. 81% of Previous campaign outcome is Unknown. Attempting to treat this will only lead to bad bias. Also, the goal of this field is same as the 'Target' variable - whether the marketing campaign resulted in customer accepting term deposits. Hence it's better to drop this field.

Insights from bivariate analysis of categorical features:¶
  1. Job types seem to have correlation to customers opting for Term Deposits. We will treat 'Unknown' type as part of data prep
  2. For marital status, the data also corraborates that we can establish this as an ordinal data type in the order of divorced, Single and Married.
  3. Default loan has almost similar distribution across both status of Target variable. Ideally we can drop this as it proves there is no major impact because of this feature.
  4. Housing loan and Personal loan seem to have some correlation enough to retain them for model prediction.
  5. For month, it appears safe to make an assumption that more number of customers contacted correlates to the higher number of customers subscribing to term deposit for that month.

Summary of Deliverable 1 - Univariate and Multivariate Analysis¶

  1. The dataset as such is highly skewed with only 11% of customers subscribing to term deposits.
  2. The correlation between most of the features are very little to none.
  3. Many of the continuous features have a large number of outliers and heavily right-skewed which needs to be corrected.
  4. The following features can be dropped since they don't differentiate much across the classes of the Target - day, contact, poutcome
  5. The following features can be considered for drop but we will compute feature importance to confirm the same - month, pdays, previous, default
  6. Some of the categorical features have 'unknown' values that needs to be corrected. Depending on the number of records, we can replace them with mode.

Summary of Deliverable 2¶

  1. Features - Day,contact and poutcome were dropped
  2. All categorical columns were first converted to datatype 'category'. On these relevant label encoding process was done
  3. Features with wide range of data were scaled - balance, duration and campaign
  4. previous and pdays are relatively correlated than other features. Since previous was label encoded, i am leaving pdays as-is. Once we run the models and see feature importances, we can determine if this has to be encoded or dropped.
  5. Training and Testing data split has been done.

Deliverable 3. Create the ensemble model¶

1. Logistic Regression and Decision tree models and their metrics¶

In [318]:
# Import all model metrics
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix,recall_score,precision_score,f1_score,roc_auc_score,accuracy_score

#Logistic Regression
termModel = LogisticRegression(random_state=7,fit_intercept=False)

#Apply model on training data
termModel.fit(X_train, y_train)                 

#Apply model on X test data to get predicted value of Y or Yhat
y_predict = termModel.predict(X_test) 

# Model metrics
print('Training accuracy = ',termModel.score(X_train,y_train))
print()
print('Testing accuracy = ',termModel.score(X_test, y_test))
print()
print('Recall = ',recall_score(y_test,y_predict))
print()
print('Precision = ',precision_score(y_test,y_predict))
print()
print('F1 score = ',f1_score(y_test,y_predict))
print()
print('ROC AUC score = ',roc_auc_score(y_test,y_predict))

#Confusion matrix
sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict),annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1])
plt.ylabel('Observed')
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.show()

3. Conclusion¶

Goal of the model is to increase the hit ratio where we need to minimize false positives. So our important metric is Precision.

Of all the algorithms I have used, Gradient Boosting has the highest precision followed by Bagging on Logistic Regression.

Another model to note here is the Regularized Decision tree. Among all algorithms used, this model has relatively better values across all metrics like Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1 Score and ROC score.

Important features:¶

The top features on the basis of coefficient as well as Features Importance are: (Based on most common top features across Logistic Regression, Decision Tree and Regularized Decision Tree)

  • Duration implying Marketing campaign should target to spend more time talking to targeted customers
  • Customers without Housing Loan
  • Customers with better account Balance
